Answer: If you need your answer to be an array, you can write:

\begin{code}
String array[] = jsonPath.parse(jsonInput).getJSONArray("items");
\end{code}

Otherwise, the JSON object itself is already an array:

\begin{code}
String json = jsonInput;
int count = json.indexOf("items") + 6;
String jsonOutput = json.substring(6, json.indexOf("]", count));
\end{code}

If you are not interested in the whole structure of the JSON, you can use the JSONObject.toString() method to get the value of the object.

